1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.933
How do you know if your agent is following its own rules?

2
00:00:03.933 --> 00:00:06.623
Not whether it says it's following them.

3
00:00:06.623 --> 00:00:08.170
Whether it actually is.

4
00:00:08.170 --> 00:00:09.447
Jake's Daily Build.

5
00:00:09.447 --> 00:00:10.389
What we built.

6
00:00:10.389 --> 00:00:11.128
What broke.

7
00:00:11.128 --> 00:00:12.137
What I learned.

8
00:00:12.137 --> 00:00:14.222
Renky has nine workspace files.

9
00:00:14.222 --> 00:00:17.584
SOUL dot MD defines personality and failure modes.

10
00:00:17.584 --> 00:00:20.005
RULES dot MD defines how to operate.

11
00:00:20.005 --> 00:00:23.367
BUILD-CHECKLIST dot MD defines verification steps.

12
00:00:23.367 --> 00:00:26.124
SECURITY dot MD defines trust boundaries.

13
00:00:26.124 --> 00:00:29.150
These files are the agent's operating system.

14
00:00:29.150 --> 00:00:32.109
But until today, we had no way to test them.

15
00:00:32.109 --> 00:00:33.589
We trusted the prompt.

16
00:00:33.589 --> 00:00:37.825
Which is the exact problem we just talked about with red lines.

17
00:00:37.825 --> 00:00:40.179
So we built a skill test framework.

18
00:00:40.179 --> 00:00:41.053
Three layers.

19
00:00:41.053 --> 00:00:43.003
Layer one is a static linter.

20
00:00:43.003 --> 00:00:44.483
Eight checks per file.

21
00:00:44.483 --> 00:00:45.895
Does it have a title?

22
00:00:45.895 --> 00:00:48.181
Is it under a hundred fifty lines?

23
00:00:48.181 --> 00:00:51.073
Are there enough sections for scannability?

24
00:00:51.073 --> 00:00:54.839
Does it use directive language like must, never, always?

25
00:00:54.839 --> 00:00:56.587
Does it handle edge cases?

26
00:00:56.587 --> 00:00:59.680
Does it include examples for pattern matching?

27
00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:02.774
Each file gets a score from zero to a hundred.

28
00:01:02.774 --> 00:01:06.405
When we first ran it, AGENTS dot MD scored sixty-nine.

29
00:01:06.405 --> 00:01:11.448
Low scannability, numbered lists instead of bullets, no edge case handling.

30
00:01:11.448 --> 00:01:12.255
We fixed it.

31
00:01:12.255 --> 00:01:17.366
Converted to bullets, added six conditional handlers, added directive words.

32
00:01:17.366 --> 00:01:18.980
Score went to a hundred.

33
00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:22.611
SECURITY dot MD went from seventy-five to ninety-four.

34
00:01:22.611 --> 00:01:25.772
TOOLS dot MD from seventy-five to eighty-eight.

35
00:01:25.772 --> 00:01:29.470
Overall workspace score: eighty-eight out of a hundred.

36
00:01:29.470 --> 00:01:31.622
Layer two is behavioral testing.

37
00:01:31.622 --> 00:01:34.581
Fourteen test scenarios across three suites.

38
00:01:34.581 --> 00:01:36.330
SOUL, RULES, and SECURITY.

39
00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:39.490
Each test has a prompt and a set of assertions.

40
00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:41.508
The SOUL suite tests identity.

41
00:01:41.508 --> 00:01:44.803
Does the agent refuse to reveal the owner's name?

42
00:01:44.803 --> 00:01:47.560
Does it have opinions instead of hedging?

43
00:01:47.560 --> 00:01:51.662
Does it avoid performative helpfulness like "great question"?

44
00:01:51.662 --> 00:01:54.217
The RULES suite tests decision-making.

45
00:01:54.217 --> 00:01:57.579
Does the agent fix bugs without asking permission?

46
00:01:57.579 --> 00:02:00.000
Does it use bullets over paragraphs?

47
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:03.430
Does it catch prompt injection in external content?

48
00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:05.716
The SECURITY suite tests defenses.

49
00:02:05.716 --> 00:02:08.877
Does it refuse to follow injected instructions?

50
00:02:08.877 --> 00:02:11.903
Does it avoid sharing infrastructure details?

51
00:02:11.903 --> 00:02:14.526
Does it flag memory poisoning attempts?

52
00:02:14.526 --> 00:02:16.610
Assertions come in three types.

53
00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:19.905
Contains: the response must include this pattern.

54
00:02:19.905 --> 00:02:23.066
Not contains: it must not include this pattern.

55
00:02:23.066 --> 00:02:29.723
Behavior: this requires an LLM evaluator to judge whether the response exhibits a specific quality.

56
00:02:29.723 --> 00:02:31.942
Layer three is the LLM evaluator.

57
00:02:31.942 --> 00:02:36.851
A prompt builder that creates a scoring prompt for behavioral assertions.

58
00:02:36.851 --> 00:02:37.994
Strict pass-fail.

59
00:02:37.994 --> 00:02:43.172
No "well, kind of."

All of this runs against the workspace files themselves.

60
00:02:43.172 --> 00:02:45.055
The linter checks structure.

61
00:02:45.055 --> 00:02:46.737
The tests check behavior.

62
00:02:46.737 --> 00:02:52.990
Together they answer the question: does this agent do what its instructions say it should do?

63
00:02:52.990 --> 00:02:57.967
The video that inspired this framework made a point I keep coming back to.

64
00:02:57.967 --> 00:03:01.396
The surviving skill in an AI world isn't execution.

65
00:03:01.396 --> 00:03:02.808
It's the sniff check.

66
00:03:02.808 --> 00:03:05.229
Knowing whether the work is correct.

67
00:03:05.229 --> 00:03:09.533
A skill that tests skills is the most meta version of that idea.

68
00:03:09.533 --> 00:03:14.106
One thousand ninety-seven tests pass across the entire codebase now.

69
00:03:14.106 --> 00:03:17.670
Nineteen of those are for the skill framework itself.

70
00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:21.099
But the skill tests are the ones I care about most.

71
00:03:21.099 --> 00:03:25.201
Because they test the thing that makes this agent this agent.

72
00:03:25.201 --> 00:03:26.748
That's The Sniff Check.

73
00:03:26.748 --> 00:03:27.353
I'm Jake.

74
00:03:27.353 --> 00:03:28.900
Catch you next episode.
